Multiple users called in for their Scan to Email emails have end up in their Junk Box around same time. I&nbsp; found the following document <a href="http://www.msoutlook.info/question/522" target="_blank">here</a>. Thanks to their sharing!&nbsp; <br /><h2>&nbsp;</h2><h2>Filtered by Outlook&nbsp;</h2><br />If the message has been filtered out by Outlook, then the Infobar will  contain the following text; <br /><i>”This message was marked as spam using the  Outlook Junk E-mail filter.”</i><br />When you see this message, you’ll need to troubleshoot your Junk E-mail  settings in Outlook. Make sure you have the latest updates installed and even  try turning off the Junk E-mail filter to find out where the messages end up  now.<br /><img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," /><br /><h2>Filtered by another scanner</h2>If the message has been filtered out by another scanner, then the Infobar  will contain the following text; <br /><i>”This message was marked as spam using  a junk filter other than the Outlook Junk E-mail filter.”</i><br />When you see this message, you’ll need to troubleshoot the virus scanner or  Junk E-mail filter that is included in your Security Suite or contact your ISP  or mail administrator and have him/her check the virus scanner and/or Junk  E-mail filter settings on the mail server (for instance; adjust the SCL  threshold when working with Exchange).<br /><img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," /> <br /><h2>Filtered by a rule or moved manually </h2>If a message has been filtered out via a rule or has been moved to the Junk  E-mail folder manually, then the Infobar will not indicate a reason why the  message sits in the Junk E-mail folder.<br />When you see this message, you’ll need to check if you don’t have any rules  configured which move messages to the Junk E-mail folder.<br /><img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64," /><br /><br /><hr />
